{
  "doc_id": "35858",
  "text": "One intriguing possibility that may underlie some of the common actions of 3a,5a-THP is its effects on neuroplasticity. For example, naked mole rats that are breeders have more favorable neural morphology than do non-breeders [CITATION_1] . Given that 3a,5a-THP is elevated in brain during pregnancy and that 3a,5a-THP has demonstrated trophic effects, the extent to which 3a,5a-THP may influence behavior associated with parity is of interest. Parity enhances cognitive function and affective behavior [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Furthermore, following mating and pregnancy, there is enhancement of neurogenesis in the hippocampus [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Indeed, rats with greater parity have more neurogenesis in the hippocampus. In our hands, we see that multiparous rats perform better on hippocampally mediated tasks (elevated plus maze, Fig. 6 ; object recognition, Fig. 7 ), than do nulliparous and/or primiparous rats and enhancements in cognitive performance occur concomitant with enhancements in circulating 3a,5a-THP among primiparous dams, albeit causal effects have not been established [CITATION_8] . For this reason, we will examine acute and longlasting effects of mating and/or parity on social experience on SCEP.",
